Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: KenolKobil, Total Kenya Are Active

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-03-25T16:25:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-25/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenolkobil-total-kenya-are-active.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index retreated
0.1 percent to 71.76, a seventh day of declines, by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rallied for a fifth day, adding
0.2 percent to 1,993.32 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index slipped 0.8 percent
to 24,863.38 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-
mailed statement from the bourse. Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall
Index (FTN098)  climbed for a seventh day, adding 0.1 percent to 866.19 by
5 p.m. in Windhoek, while the Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index declined 0.1 percent to 1,056.18 by 3 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN), a fuel retailer with operations
in seven African nations, rose the most in almost two weeks,
gaining 20 cents, or 2.2 percent, to 9.5 shillings after
yesterday forecasting “double-digit” first-half earnings
growth following a 38 percent jump in full-year profit.  “The positive outlook of the company could generate
increased interest in the stock,” Nairobi-based Sterling
Investment Bank Ltd. said in an e-mailed note to clients today.  Total Kenya Ltd. (TKNL)  ,  Total SA (FP) ’s unit in the East
African nation, retreated for a third day, losing 25 cents, or
0.9 percent, to 26.75 shillings. Oil fell for a second day in
 New York  as crude failed to breach technical resistance at its
30-month high and on concern that the European debt situation
and the crisis in  Japan  will curb fuel demand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
